# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: counter-rotating-propellers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The **Airbus A400M Atlas** is a European four-engine turboprop military transport aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It was designed by Airbus Military, now Airbus Defence and Space, as a tactical airlifter with strategic capabilities to replace older transport aircraft such as the Transall C-160 and the Lockheed C-130 Hercules.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M is sized between the C-130 and the Boeing C-17 Globemaster III.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It can carry heavier loads than the C-130 and can use rough landing strips.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In addition to its transport capabilities, the A400M can perform aerial refueling and medical evacuation when fitted with appropriate equipment.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M's maiden flight took place on 11 December 2009 from Seville Airport, Spain.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Between 2009 and 2010, the A400M faced cancellation as a result of development programme delays and cost overruns; however, the customer nations chose to maintain their support for the project.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A total of 174 A400M aircraft had been ordered by eight nations by July 2011.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In March 2013, the A400M received European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) certification and the first aircraft was delivered to the French Air Force in August 2013.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Varying requirements and the complications of international politics meant that progress on the initiative was slow.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In 1989, Lockheed decided to withdraw from the grouping.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Lockheed independently developed an upgraded Hercules, the C-130J Super Hercules.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] With the addition of Alenia of Italy and CASA of Spain, the FIMA group became Euroflag.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Project management evaluated twin and quad turbofan engine configurations, a quad propfan configuration, and a quad turboprop configuration, eventually settling on the turboprop option.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Since no existing turboprop engine in the western world was powerful enough to reach the projected cruise speed of Mach 0.72, a new engine design was required.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Originally, the SNECMA M138 turboprop, based on the M88 turbofan core, was selected, but this powerplant was found to be incapable of satisfying the requirements.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In April 2002, Airbus Military issued a new request for proposal (RFP), which Pratt & Whitney Canada with the PW180 and Europrop International answered.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In May 2003, Airbus Military selected the Europrop TP400-D6.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] United Technologies alleged that the selection was a result of political interference.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A Europrop partner executive said in April 2003 that Airbus was close to selecting the P&WC offer, claiming it was more than €400 million (US$436.7 million) cheaper than Europrop's bid.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A later report described the revised bid as exceeding P&WC's bid by €120 million.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The original partner nations were France, Germany, Italy, Spain, the United Kingdom, Turkey, Belgium, and Luxembourg.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] These nations decided to charge the Organisation for Joint Armament Cooperation (OCCAR) with the management of the acquisition of the A400M.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Following the withdrawal of Italy and revision of procurement totals, the revised requirement amounted to 180 aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The first flight was forecast to occur in 2008 and first delivery in 2009.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In April 2005, South Africa joined the programme, with the Denel Saab Aerostructures receiving a contract for fuselage components.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Malaysia was the second country outside Europe to be involved.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Malaysia through CTRM is responsible for manufacturing composite aero components for the aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M is positioned as an intermediate size and range between the Lockheed C-130 and the Boeing C-17, carrying cargo too large or too heavy for the C-130, while able to use rough landing strips.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In January 2009, EADS announced that the first delivery was postponed from 2009 until at least 2012, and indicated that it wanted to renegotiate.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] EADS maintained the first deliveries would begin three years after the first flight.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In January 2009, *Financial Times Deutschland* reported that the A400M was overweight by 12 tons and may not have been able to meet a key performance requirement, the ability to airlift 32 tons.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Sources told *FTD* that it could only lift 29 tons, insufficient to carry an infantry fighting vehicle like the Puma.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In response to the report, the chief of the German Air Force stated: "That is a disastrous development," and that it could delay deliveries to the German Air Force (*Luftwaffe*) until 2014.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The Initial Operational Capability (IOC) for the Luftwaffe was later delayed and alternatives, such as a higher integration of European airlift capabilities, were studied.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 29 March 2009, Airbus CEO Tom Enders told *Der Spiegel* that the programme could possibly be abandoned without changes.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] OCCAR reminded participating countries that they could terminate the contract before 31 March 2009.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In April 2009, the South African Air Force announced that it was considering alternatives to the A400M due to delays and increased cost.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 5 November 2009, South Africa announced the cancellation of its order.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 12 June, *The New York Times* reported that Germany and France had delayed a decision whether to cancel their orders for six months while the UK planned to decide in late June.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In 2009, Airbus acknowledged that the programme was expected to lose at least €2.4 billion and could not break even without export sales.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A PricewaterhouseCoopers audit projected that it would run €11.2 billion over budget, and that corrective measures would result in an overrun of €7.6 billion.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 24 July 2009, the seven European nations announced that the programme would proceed and formed a joint procurement agency to renegotiate the contract.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 9 December 2009, the *Financial Times* reported that Airbus requested an additional €5 billion subsidy.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In January 2010, Airbus repeated that the A400M could possibly be scrapped, costing it €5.7 billion unless €5.3 billion was added by partner governments.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Delays had already increased its budget by 25%.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Airbus executives reportedly regarded the A400M as competing for resources with the A380 and A350 XWB programmes.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In June 2009, Lockheed Martin said that both the UK and France had requested details on the C-130J as an alternative to the A400M.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In November 2010, Belgium, Britain, France, Germany, Luxembourg, Spain and Turkey finalised the contract and agreed to lend Airbus Military €1.5 billion.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The programme was then at least three years behind schedule.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The UK reduced its order from 25 to 22 aircraft and Germany from 60 to 53, decreasing the total order from 180 to 170.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In 2013, France's budget for 50 aircraft was €8.9 billion (~US$11.7 billion) at a unit cost of €152.4 million (~US$200 million), or €178 million (~US$235 million) including development costs.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The 2013 French White Paper on Defence and National Security cut the tactical transport aircraft requirement from 70 to 50.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] As the A400M was unable to perform helicopter in-flight refuelling, France announced in 2016 that it would purchase four C-130Js.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In July 2016, French aerospace laboratory ONERA confirmed successful wind tunnel trials of a 36.5 m (120 ft) hose and drogue configuration to permit helicopter refuelling by the A400M.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Prior tests found instability in the intended 24 m (79 ft) hose due to vortices generated by the spoilers, deployed to achieve 108-130 kt air speed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In April 2016, production faults affecting 14 propeller gearboxes (PGBs) produced by Italian supplier Avio Aero were discovered.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The issue, involving a heat treatment process that weakened the ring gear, affected no other PGBs; the units involved needed changing.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Only engines 1 and 3, which have propellers that rotate to the right, were affected.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) issued an Airworthiness Directive mandating immediate on-wing inspection, followed by replacement if evidence of damage was found.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 27 April 2016, Airbus warned there may be a substantial PGB repair cost.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] An interim PGB fix was certified in July 2016, greatly extending inspection intervals.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In May 2016, Airbus confirmed that a cracking behaviour identified during quality control checks in 2011 was found in a French A400M's fuselage part.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Not impacting safety, it could be repaired during regular maintenance/upgrade schedules.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The aluminium-zinc alloy, known as 7000 series, was used in several central frames.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Its chemistry, along with environmental conditions, led to crack propagation.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The alloy was excluded from future aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A retrofit to remove it from early A400Ms, which could take up to seven months, was considered.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 27 July 2016, Airbus confirmed that it took a US$1 billion charge over delivery issues and export prospects.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Before the first flight, required airborne test time on the Europrop TP400 engine was achieved using a C-130 testbed aircraft, which first flew on 17 December 2008.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 11 December 2009, the A400M's maiden flight was carried out from Seville.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In April 2010, the second A400M made its first flight.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In July 2010, the third A400M took to the air, at which point the fleet had flown 400 hours over more than 100 flights.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In July 2010, the A400M passed ultimate-load testing of the wing.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In October 2010, Airbus announced the start of refuelling and air-drop tests.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] By October 2010, the A400M had flown 672 hours of the 2,700 hours expected to reach certification.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In November 2010, the first paratroop jumps were performed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Enders and A400M project manager Bruno Delannoy were among the skydivers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In late 2010, simulated icing tests were performed on the MSN1 flight test aircraft using devices installed on the wing's leading edges.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] These revealed an aerodynamic issue causing horizontal tail buffeting, resolved via a six-week retrofit to install anti-icing equipment fed with bleed air.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Production aircraft are similarly fitted.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Winter tests were done in Kiruna, Sweden in February 2011.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In March 2012, high-altitude start and landing tests were performed at La Paz at 4,061.5 m (13,325 ft) and Cochabamba at 2,548 m (8,360 feet) in Bolivia.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] By April 2011, a total of 1,400 flight hours over 450 flights had been achieved.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In May 2011, the TP400-D6 engine received certification from the EASA.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In May 2011, the A400M fleet had totalled 1,600 hours over 500 flights.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] By September 2011, the total increased to 2,100 hours and 684 flights.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Due to a gearbox problem, an A400M was shown on static display instead of a flight demonstration at the 2011 Paris Air Show.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] By October 2011, total flight hours had reached 2,380 over 784 flights.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In May 2012, the MSN2 flight test aircraft was due to spend a week conducting unpaved runway trials on a grass strip at Cottbus-Drewitz Airport in Germany.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Testing was cut short on 23 May, when, during a rejected takeoff test, the left side main wheels broke through the runway surface.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Airbus Military stated that it found the aircraft's behaviour was "excellent".
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The undamaged aircraft returned to Toulouse.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In March 2013, the A400M was granted type certification by the EASA, clearing its entry to service.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Assembly of the first A400M began at the Seville plant of EADS Spain in early 2007.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Major assemblies built at other facilities abroad were brought to the Seville facility by Airbus Beluga transporters.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In February 2008, four Europrop TP400-D6 flight test engines were delivered for the first A400M.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Static structural testing of a test airframe began in March 2008 in Spain.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] By 2010, Airbus planned to manufacture 30 aircraft per year.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The Turkish partner, Turkish Aerospace Industries, delivered the first A400M component to Bremen in 2007.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The first flight, originally scheduled for early 2008, was postponed due to delays and financial pressures.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] EADS announced in January 2008 that engine issues had been responsible for the delay.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The rescheduled first flight, set for July 2008, was again postponed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Civil certification under EASA CS-25 was followed by certification for military uses.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In June 2008, the A400M was rolled out in Seville at an event presided by King Juan Carlos I of Spain.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 12 January 2011, serial production began.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In August 2013, the first A400M was delivered to the French Air Force.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It was formally handed over during a ceremony in September 2013.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In August 2013, the first Turkish A400M conducted its maiden flight from Seville.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In March 2015, Malaysia received its first A400M.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In May 2015, it was revealed that the member nations had created a Programme Monitoring Team (PMT) to review and monitor progress in the A400M's development and production.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The PMT inspects the final assembly line in Seville and other production sites.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Early conclusions observed that Airbus lacked an integrated approach to production, development and retrofits, treating these as separate programmes.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 9 May 2015, an A400M crashed in Seville on its first test flight.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Germany, Malaysia, Turkey and UK suspended flights during the investigation.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Initial focus centered on whether the crash had been caused by new fuel supply management software for trimming the fuel tanks to enable certain manoeuvres; Airbus issued an update instructing operators to inspect all Engine Control Units (ECUs).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A key scenario examined by investigators was that the torque calibration parameter data had accidentally been wiped on three engines during software installation, preventing FADEC operations.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 11 June 2015, Spain's Ministry of Defence announced that prototypes could restart test flights and that further permits could soon be granted.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The RAF lifted its suspension on A400M flights on 16 June 2015, followed the next day by the Turkish Air Force.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In June 2016, the French Air Force accepted its ninth A400M, the first capable of conducting tactical tasks such as airdropping supplies.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The revised standard includes the addition of cockpit armour and defensive aids system equipment, plus clearance to transfer and receive fuel in-flight.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The Airbus A400M provides substantial improvements to payload, range, internal volume and operational capacity over the Transall C-160 and Lockheed C-130 that it replaces or augments.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The cargo box is 17.71 m (58.1 ft) long excluding ramp, 4.00 m (13.12 ft) wide, and 3.85 m (12.6 ft) high (or 4.00 m (13.12 ft) aft of the wing). and can be configured to transport cargo or military personnel, drop paratroops, conduct medical evacuations or carry out aerial refuelling.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It can operate out of short, soft landing strips and fly long-range cargo.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A typical cargo load might include six Land Rovers and their trailers, or two light armoured vehicles, or a dump truck and excavator, or a Patriot missile system, or a Puma or Cougar helicopter, or a truck and 25-ton trailer.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M features a fly-by-wire flight control system with sidestick controllers and flight envelope protection.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Like other Airbus aircraft, it has a full glass cockpit.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Most systems are loosely based on those of the A380, but modified for the military mission.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The hydraulic system has dual 20.7 MPa (3,000 psi) channels powering the primary and secondary flight-control actuators, landing gear, wheel brakes, cargo door and optional hose-and-drogue refuelling system.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] As with the A380, there is no third hydraulic system.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Instead, there are two electrical systems.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] One is a set of dual-channel electrically powered hydraulic actuators, the other an array of electrically/hydraulically powered hybrid actuators.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The dissimilar redundancy provides more protection against battle damage.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The DE DIRCM system, provided by Diehl Defence GmbH & Co.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] KG and based on Elbit Systems Ltd.'s J-MUSIC technology, enhances the aircraft's self-protection capabilities against infrared-guided missiles.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The contract was scheduled to be performed over a four-year period.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] More than 30 percent of the airplane's structure is made of composite materials.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The 42.4 m (139 ft) span wing is primarily made of carbon fibre reinforced plastic components, including the wing spars, the 19 m (62 ft) long, 12–14 mm (0.47–0.55 in) thick wingskins, and other parts.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The wing weighs about 6,500 kg (14,330 lb), and it can carry and lift up to 25,000 kg (55,116 lb) of fuel.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It has an aspect ratio of 8.1, a wide chord of 5.6 m (18 ft), and a sweep angle of 15 degrees at 25 percent mean aerodynamic chord.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Its vertical stabiliser is 8.02 m (26.3 ft) tall.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The horizontal stabiliser spans 19.03 m (62.4 ft), with a sweep of 32.5 degrees.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The Ratier-Figeac FH385 propellers turn counterclockwise and the FH386 clockwise.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The eight-bladed scimitar propellers are made from a woven composite material.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The aircraft is powered by four Europrop TP400-D6 engines rated at 8,250 kW (11,000 hp) each.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The TP400-D6 engine is the most powerful turboprop engine in the West to enter operational use.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The pair of propellers on each wing turn in opposite directions, with the tips of the propellers advancing from above towards the midpoint between the two engines.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] This is in contrast to the overwhelming majority of multi-engine propeller driven aircraft where all propellers turn in the same direction.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The counter-rotation is achieved by the use of a gearbox fitted to two of the engines, and only the propeller turns in the opposite direction.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] All four engines are identical and turn in the same direction.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] This eliminates the need to have two different "handed" engines on stock for the same aircraft, simplifying maintenance and supply costs.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] This configuration, dubbed *down between engines* (DBE), allows the engine to produce more lift and lessens the torque and prop wash on each wing.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It also reduces yaw in the event of an outboard engine failure.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Due to these benefits, the vertical stabiliser can be reduced by 17 percent in size, while the size of the horizontal stabiliser can be shrunk by 8 percent.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] A forward-looking infrared enhanced vision system (EVS) camera provides an enhanced terrain view in low-visibility conditions.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The EVS imagery is displayed on the HUD for low-altitude flying, demonstrating its value for flying tactical missions at night or in clouds.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] EADS and Thales provide the new Multi-Colour Infrared Alerting Sensor (MIRAS) missile warning sensor for the A400M.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M has a removable refuelling probe mounted above the cockpit, allowing it to receive fuel from drogue-equipped tankers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Optionally, the receiving probe can be replaced with a fuselage-mounted UARRSI receptacle for receiving fuel from boom equipped tankers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The aircraft can act as a tanker when fitted with two wing mounted hose and drogue under-wing refuelling pods or a centre-line Hose and Drum unit.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The refuelling pods can transfer fuel to other aircraft at a rate of 20.0 kg/s (2,640 lb/min).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M features deployable baffles in front of the rear side doors, intended to give paratroops time to get clear of the aircraft before they are hit by the slipstream.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The A400M is designed as a multirole aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In June 2026, France became the launch customer for the A400M Parallel Mission System (PMS) upgrade.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 29 December 2013, the French Air Force performed the A400M's first operational mission: an aircraft flew to Mali in support of Operation Serval.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 10 September 2015, the RAF was declared the A400M fleet leader in terms of flying hours, with 900 hours flown over 300 sorties, achieved by a fleet of four aircraft.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Glen Willcox of the RAF's Heavy Aircraft Test Squadron confirmed that reliability levels were high for an aircraft so early in its career, and that night vision goggle trials, hot and cold soaking, noise characterisation tests and the first tie-down schemes for cargo had already been completed.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In March 2015, the RAF's first operational mission occurred, flying cargo to RAF Akrotiri, Cyprus.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In September and October 2017, A400Ms from France, Germany and the UK participated in disaster relief operations following Hurricane Irma in the Caribbean, delivering a Puma helicopter, food, water and other aid supplies, and evacuating stranded people.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In July 2018, the German Luftwaffe used an A400M in combat conditions for the first time, transporting 75 soldiers from Wunstorf Air Base to Mazar-i-Sharif, Afghanistan.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] German Air Force Inspector Ingo Gerhartz called this a "milestone" because it was the first such mission in an active war zone and showed that the armouring kit was fully functional.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In September 2018, the French Air and Space Force announced that they had logged 10,000 flying hours with their fleet of 14 A400Ms, mostly flying supply missions for Operation Barkhane.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The German government had planned to sell the last 13 A400Ms out of its order of 53 aircraft but failed to attract any buyers.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In 2017, the German parliament decided to employ them in service at Wunstorf in northern Germany instead.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In January 2019, German Minister of Defence Ursula von der Leyen announced that 10 A400Ms were to be used to form a multinational airlift wing based at Lechfeld Air Base in southern Germany.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The plan was abandoned in 2022 due to a lack of interest from potential partner nations.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In 2019, a German A400M tanker replaced the Airbus A310 MRTT deployed to Muwaffaq Salti Air Base in Jordan, to refuel allied aircraft as part of the German intervention against ISIL.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In August 2021, a total of 25 A400Ms were deployed by Belgium, France, Germany, Spain, Turkey and the UK to assist in the Kabul Airport evacuations.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] German A400Ms evacuated 5,347 people over the course of 35 flights.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In September 2023, Royal Air Force A400M transported British search and rescue teams to Morocco after a Mw 6.9 earthquake had ravaged the country.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In October 2024, the German Air Force tested the A400M's "mixed airdrop" capability at Scheuen drop zone at Air Base Celle, combining personnel and cargo drops from 400 meters at 220 km/h in different configurations.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Overseen by BAAINBw, the trials built on earlier NATO-standard CDS pallet trials conducted during Grafenwöhr exercises in 2020 and confirmed the A400M's ability to deploy up to 4 metric tons of cargo and 108 paratroopers in a single sortie.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Final military certification depends on further trials and data analysis, while Airbus certification has been granted.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] On 9 May 2026, a Royal Air Force A400M dropped a specialist UK military team that executed a first-of-its-kind emergency humanitarian mission, parachuting onto Tristan da Cunha, an archipelago in the South Atlantic Ocean considered to be among the world's most remote islands.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The team was sent to treat a British national with suspected hantavirus; he was a local island resident who disembarked from the virus-hit cruise ship MV Hondius.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Oxygen supplies at the island's hospital had reached a critical level.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The territory normally operates with just a two-person medical team.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Six paratroopers and two military clinicians from the 16 Air Assault Brigade launched the mission.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Because of the specialised medical care required, an intensive care nurse and an intensive care doctor were strapped to paratroopers for tandem jumps.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The team flew 6,788 km from RAF Brize Norton to Ascension Island.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] They then flew over 3,000 km to the drop zone, supported by mid-air refuelling from an RAF Voyager.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Medics battled winds exceeding 25 mph to land safely on the island's rocky golf course.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Simultaneously, an RAF A400M air-dropped 3.3 tonnes of vital medical aid and oxygen.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In February 2017, the Czech Ministries of Defence stated they were interested in a joint lease of A400Ms from Germany.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In January 2017, Indonesia approved the acquisition of five A400Ms to boost its military airlift capabilities.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] had signed a deal for two A400Ms, with a letter of intent option for four more.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The contract was finalised in December 2022.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] announced the government was considering procuring four additional A400Ms.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] It was expected to be delivered to Kazakhstan before 2025.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] ordered four A400Ms to supplement its fleet of C-130 Hercules.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] million, with the nation joining the Airbus Military team as an industrial partner.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Deliveries were expected from 2010 to 2012.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] In 2009, South Africa cancelled all eight aircraft, citing increasing costs.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Five prototype and development aircraft; a sixth aircraft was cancelled.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] An A400M crashed on 9 May 2015, when aircraft MSN23, on its first test flight crashed shortly after take-off from San Pablo Airport in Seville, Spain, killing four Spanish Airbus crew and seriously injuring two others.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] Once airborne, the crew contacted air traffic controllers just before the crash about a technical failure, before colliding with an electricity pylon while attempting an emergency landing.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/airbus-a400m-atlas] The crash was attributed to the FADEC system being unable to read engine sensors properly due to an accidental file-wipe, resulting in three of its four engines remaining in "idle" mode during takeoff.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] The propellers on most conventional twin-engined aircraft turn clockwise (as viewed from behind the engine).
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] Counter-rotating propellers generally turn clockwise on the left engine and counterclockwise on the right.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] The advantage of such designs is that counter-rotating propellers balance the effects of torque and P-factor, meaning that such aircraft do not have a critical engine in the case of engine failure.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] Drawbacks of counter-rotating propellers come from the fact that, in order to reverse the rotation of one propeller, either one propeller must have an additional reversing gearbox, or the engines themselves must be adapted to turn in opposite directions.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] Counter-rotating propellers have been used since the earliest days of aviation, in order to avoid the aircraft tipping sideways from the torque reaction against propellers turning in a single direction.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] They were fitted to the very first controlled powered aeroplane, the *Wright Flyer*, and to other subsequent types such as the Dunne D.1 of 1907 and the more successful Dunne D.5 of 1910.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] In designing the Lockheed P-38 Lightning, the decision was made to reverse the counter-rotation such that the tops of the propeller arcs move outwards (counterclockwise on the left and clockwise on the right), away from each other.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] Tests on the initial XP-38 prototype demonstrated greater accuracy in gunnery with the unusual configuration.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] The aerodynamics of a propeller on one side of an aircraft change according to which way it turns, as it affects the P-factor.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] This can in turn affect performance under extreme conditions and therefore flight safety certification.
[src:counter-rotating-propellers/counter-rotating-propellers] Some modern types, such as the Airbus A400M, have counter-rotating propellers in order to meet air safety requirements under engine-out conditions.
